doc.after: The Joint Typhoon Warning Center (JTWC)[nb 2] first monitored an area of disturbed weather on SeptemberÂ 25.[2] At the time, the system consisted of a weak circulation, but with good outflow and located in an area of low wind shear.[3] The system moved to the west-northwest, steered by a subtropical ridge to the east of Japan.[2] On SeptemberÂ 26, a tropical depression developed about 925Â km (575Â mi) east of the Northern Marianas Islands, and also to the south of the Japanese island of Minamitorishima.[2][4] Later that day, the Japan Meteorological Agency (JMA)[nb 3] upgraded the depression to Tropical Storm Higos,[4] at the same time that the JTWC also upgraded to a tropical storm.[2] By that time, the system had developed an organized area of convection.[3]
